= Conclusion

We have presented the LaSalle Wiki Tutor, a deployed AI study advisor for La Salle Campus Barcelona that takes a tools-over-wiki approach to a mid-scale bilingual academic catalog. The system makes four contributions. The crawl-and-render pipeline produces a structured Markdown wiki with strict YAML frontmatter through field-targeted extraction rather than whole-page Markdown conversion, with a measured fallback rate of 1.6%. The ten-tool surface lets a streaming Agno + OpenAI agent answer the catalog-shaped questions we observed in production within the system prompt's five-tool-call ceiling, with the same prompt enforcing scope guardrails and refusal patterns we measured against an adversarial spot-check. The hybrid retrieval inside `search_programs` blends BM25-F field-weighted lexical scoring with Model2Vec 256-dimensional static embeddings at a 0.55/0.45 ratio after pool-normalisation, and is the only ranker mode of the four we tested that reaches 100% top-5 coverage on a 20-query benchmark. The observability runtime stores three MongoDB collections that supply the empirical material for every measurement in this paper, including the production per-tool latency, per-turn cost, and refusal-correctness evidence we report.

The system runs publicly at #link("https://lasalle.generateeve.com") behind a shared-token gate, on a single Terraform-provisioned `t3.micro` at approximately fourteen US dollars per month. The source is open at #link("https://github.com/joe-carr-data/lasalle-wiki-tutor"). The wiki corpus is distributed as a GitHub Release asset for reproducibility; the per-paper data files and figure-generation scripts ship with the manuscript source under `paper/`.

The thesis the paper has tried to defend is narrow and empirical: for knowledge bases that are bounded, structured, slowly changing, and frontmatter-heavy, a compiled wiki navigated by deterministic tools is a more honest substrate than the default chunk-and-embed RAG pipeline, and vector retrieval continues to earn its place when confined to the single tool where literal-token overlap fails. Two directions follow naturally. The pattern should extend to multi-institution catalogs in the same vertical -- a higher-education advisor that spans several universities would inherit most of the design without requiring a redesign of the tool surface. The trace store should grow into a downstream observable for institutional analytics, since the per-turn reasoning passages and tool timings already form a structured record of what prospective students ask and how the agent answers. Both extensions follow from the same commitment: the catalog is the source of truth, and the agent is a careful navigator.
